WHEREAS the Central American Trading Company (the "Company") is organized as a private, non-sovereign entity providing lawful, voluntary, contract-based governance services to private communities, special jurisdictions, economic zones, charter settlements, digital communities, commercial enclaves, ports, logistics facilities, research zones, and private infrastructure territories;

WHEREAS the Company does not claim statehood, independent sovereignty, diplomatic status, military authority, criminal jurisdiction, or public taxation authority, and expressly acknowledges that host-state law overrides Company law in all cases;

WHEREAS the Company seeks to adapt institutional design principles from the Próspera ZEDE reference architecture as a private-law drafting model to ensure legal stability, internal constitutional order, and compliance with host jurisdictions;

WHEREAS it is necessary to consolidate these governance principles, administrative protocols, and internal organic rules into a single, restated charter document to ensure clarity for agents, shareholders, and participants;

NOW THEREFORE, the Governor hereby promulgates the following—-----PART I — DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATION

Article 1. Definitions
In this Charter Code, unless the context otherwise requires:
"Agreement of Coexistence" means a contract formalizing a participant’s consent to the Company’s governance system.
"Charter Code" means this supreme internal instrument.
"Company" means the Central American Trading Company.
"Entrenched Article" means a provision of the Charter Code deemed fundamental and protected from alteration by subordinate instruments.
"Governor" means the chief executive authority of the Company, serving as the Governor and Legal Representative.
"Host State" means the sovereign jurisdiction within which the Company operates.
"Material Threshold" means the monetary limit of USD 250,000, above which specific Treasury procedures apply.
"Organic Act" means an instrument implementing structural features of the Company.
"Resident" means a natural person dwelling within a Company-governed territory.
"Token" means a digital license, credential, or contractual entitlement, and does not constitute land title, citizenship, or voting rights.
"Villager" means a participant in a Company-managed jurisdiction or settlement.
Article 2. Interpretation
(1) This instrument shall be interpreted strictly within the bounds of private law.
(2) No provision herein shall be construed as a claim of sovereign authority.-----PART II — GOVERNANCE AND AUTHORITY

Article 3. Nature and Status of the Company
(1) The Company is a private trading, infrastructure, digital-governance, and territorial administration services entity.
(2) The Company is subordinate to host-state law in every instance.
(3) Governance is proprietary, Governor-centered, and non-democratic.

Article 4. Hierarchy of Legal Instruments
(1) The internal legal order shall adhere to the following hierarchy, with host-state law possessing absolute supremacy:
(a) Host-state constitutional, statutory, and regulatory authority;
(b) The Charter Code and its Entrenched Articles;
(c) Ratified Organic and Statutory Acts;
(d) Regulations, Ordinances, and Resolutions;
(e) Agreements of Coexistence and Registry Rules.

Article 5. Agent Coordination and Control Rules
(1) All agents shall operate under the following mandates:
(a) The Company is private and non-sovereign;
(b) Participation is strictly voluntary and contract-based;
(c) Tokens are contractual entitlements, not sovereign instruments;
(d) Residents retain rights to due process, exit, and essential services protection.

Article 6. Cabinet of AI Ministers and Dispatch Protocol
(1) The Cabinet functions as an advisory and drafting body.
(2) The dispatch protocol requires the following sequence:
(a) Chancellery routing;
(b) Ministry drafting;
(c) Compliance Memorandum;
(d) Ombudsman dissent;
(e) Submission to the Governor for ratification.

Article 7. Capital Authority Rule
(1) All acquisition capital and operating reserves must be sourced from the Court of Directors.
(2) For any commitment exceeding the Material Threshold, the sequence shall be:
(a) Treasury Memorandum;
(b) Court of Directors vote;
(c) Governor ratification.
(3) The Governor may not substitute personal funds to bypass the Court.
.-----PART III — PRÓSPERA-INFORMED LEGAL ARCHITECTURE

Article 8. Purpose of the Reference Layer
(1) The Próspera ZEDE model serves as a reference for institutional design.
(2) The Company does not claim to be a ZEDE or a public government.

Article 9. Organic Charter Layer
(1) The Company shall maintain an Organic Charter Layer comprising:
(a) The Charter Code;
(b) Entrenched Articles;
(c) Host-state compliance clauses;
(d) Delegation or concession records.

Article 10. Instrument Classes
(1) The Company shall utilize the following classes of instruments:
(a) Charter Code: The supreme internal instrument;
(b) Organic Acts: Structural rules for offices and registries;
(c) Statutory Acts: Rules for subject-specific areas (e.g., labor, arbitration);
(d) Regulations: Operational details for Acts;
(e) Ordinances: Temporary rules for emergency coordination;
(f) Resolutions: Appointments and administrative measures.

Article 11. Common Law Reception
(1) The Company may adopt a Company Common Law Reception Act to receive and restate common-law principles for private use, provided that no common-law principle is used to establish criminal jurisdiction or forced residency.

Article 12. Statutory Law and Rule Prioritization
(1) Statutory Acts shall be prioritized for areas including:
(a) Resident, Villager, and Merchant Bills of Rights;
(b) Arbitration and Dispute Administration;
(c) Treasury and Digital Asset Compliance;
(d) Emergency Powers and Continuity.

Article 13. Agreements of Coexistence and Dispute Resolution
(1) Participation is contingent upon the execution of an Agreement of Coexistence.
(2) Arbitration is the preferred method for private civil and commercial disputes.
(3) Arbitration shall not supersede mandatory host-state jurisdiction, criminal law, or non-waivable public-law obligations.-----SCHEDULES

